03793nam a22004455i 9780804764834DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047648347 a10.1515/97808047648342doi  a(DE-B1597)582432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0040002bisacsh1 aShapiro, Ann-Louise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreaking the Codes :bFemale Criminality in Fin-de-Siècle Paris /cAnn-Louise Shapiro. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (280 p.) :billus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIllustration -- tIntroduction -- t1 Crime and Culture: The "Problem" of the Female Criminal -- t2 Telling Criminal Stories -- t3 Disordered Bodies, Disorderly Acts: Medical Discourse and the Female Criminal -- t4 Love Stories: Female Crimes of Passion -- t5 The Sexual Politics of Female Criminality -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBreaking the Codes is a cultural history of the fin-de-siecle that uses the "problem" of the criminal woman to examine both the debates around the appropriate place of women in French society and the ways in which issues of gender were central to the most important cultural transformations of the period. The author asserts that "female criminality" was a code that condensed and obscured larger concerns. For example, to what degree and in what ways did the symbolic overtones of female criminality connect to the substantive issues that appeared over and over again in the stories of women's crime? How were the crimes of domestic violence, infanticide, and abortion interpreted in the context of broader debates about divorce, depopulation, sexuality, and women's roles in the public sphere? What was the role of expert commentary - from the forensic psychiatrist, the criminologist, the legal scholar - in producing a normative code for female behavior? And how did this code accommodate or resist the newly recognized voice of popular opinion and changing notions of citizenship? This study demonstrates both the inadequacy of the categories of public and private as they have been conventionally used to segregate the subjects of historical inquiry and the artificiality of the boundaries between high and low culture. Instead, it moves between domestic life and public courtrooms, between social science literature and popular journalism, analyzing the complex responses to female crime among different constituencies and through different genres. In so doing, the author sheds light on various overlapping processes of cultural negotiation in a period of profound change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- European. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476483440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764834/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles